SIMPLE: pip
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pip
<hw>Pip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pippe</ets>, D.
<ets>pip</ets>, or F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧pie</ets>; from LL.
<ets>pipita</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pituita</ets> slime, phlegm, rheum, in
fowls, the pip. Cf. <er>Pituite</er>.]</ety> <def>A contagious disease
of fowls, characterized by hoarseness, discharge from the nostrils and
eyes, and an accumulation of mucus in the mouth, forming a
⟦ldquo⟧scale⟦rdquo⟧ on the tongue. By some the term <xex>pip</xex> is
restricted to this last symptom, the disease being called
<xex>roup</xex> by them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pip
<hw>Pip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly <ets>pippin</ets>,
<ets>pepin</ets>. Cf. <er>Pippin</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A
seed, as of an apple or orange.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pip
<hw>Pip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. for <ets>pick</ets>, F.
<ets>pique</ets> a spade at cards, a pike. Cf. <er>Pique</er>.]</ety>
<def>One of the conventional figures or ⟦ldquo⟧spots⟦rdquo⟧ on playing
cards, dominoes, etc.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pip
<hw>Pip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Peep</er>.]</ety>
<def>To cry or chirp, as a chicken; to peep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To hear the chick <qex>pip</qex> and cry in the egg.</q>
<rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pipa</ent>⟦br⟧
